  "Idea": "This research introduces a novel paradigm called Meta-Curvature Guided Self-Supervised Integration (MC-GSSI), which enables robust collective relation integration across knowledge graphs (KGs) with near-zero entity overlap by dynamically discovering and refining structurally informative subgraphs through a meta-learning framework driven by discrete curvature signals. While existing methods rely on fixed geometric filters or static motif extraction, MC-GSSI treats the identification of semantically transferable relational schemas as a learnable process conditioned on integration performance. We introduce a dual-phase architecture: (1) A Curvature-Aware Motif Generator that computes Forman-Ricci curvature across edges and identifies candidate structural motifs—subgraphs centered on negative-curvature 'bottlenecks' that bridge dense clusters—as potential sources of cross-KG relational analogies. These motifs are encoded into spectral signatures using higher-order graph wavelets and matched across KGs via differentiable kernel alignment, generating an initial set of pseudo-parallel relation instances. (2) A Meta-Topological Refinement Loop that trains a lightweight controller network to adaptively re-weight nodes and edges in each KG based on their contribution to downstream alignment accuracy. Using a reptile-style meta-learning objective, the controller receives gradients from the relation integration model’s performance on validation seeds and updates the curvature computation weights to emphasize topologically coherent yet semantically discriminative regions in future iterations. This creates a feedback loop: better alignments improve motif selection, which enhances pseudo-data quality, leading to stronger representations. To ensure fidelity, we design a confidence-aware Graph Transformer with gated message passing, where synthetic triples are injected with attenuation proportional to their match stability across meta-updates. Crucially, our model jointly optimizes entity and relation embeddings without pre-aligned seeds by treating pseudo-motif pairs as self-supervised anchors, allowing emergent alignment through functional equivalence rather than lexical similarity. This approach enables zero-shot transfer of relational semantics across domains (e.g., aligning clinical ontologies with social commonsense graphs) and fundamentally advances unsupervised graph integration by making structural informativeness a dynamic, task-driven property rather than a static heuristic.",
